        body: 'The data for supplier scorecards comes from three sources that need to be connected. Your PoS transaction data provides sell-through rates, selling prices achieved, markdown frequency, return rates, and customer feedback if captured at the register. This is the richest data source and the one most retailers underutilize for supplier evaluation. Your purchasing records provide invoice costs, order quantities, order dates, and payment terms. Connecting purchasing records to PoS data by supplier and product allows margin calculations that account for actual selling prices rather than intended prices. Your receiving logs, whether maintained in the PoS inventory module or separately, provide delivery dates and order accuracy data. Comparing the promised delivery date against the actual receiving date for each order builds the delivery reliability metric. If your system does not track receiving dates, start logging them. Even a simple spreadsheet recording order number, expected date, and actual receipt date provides enough data for meaningful reliability scoring after a few months. The organizational challenge is mapping products to suppliers consistently. Ensure every product in your PoS catalog is tagged with a supplier identifier so that transaction data can be aggregated at the vendor level. Products from multiple suppliers need clear attribution so each vendor is evaluated only on their own products. Once this mapping is in place, scorecard calculations become automated queries rather than manual data compilation exercises. AskBiz supports supplier tagging at the product level, automatically aggregating vendor-level performance metrics from your daily transaction data.'
